	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />NROM-368 is mostly just a definition of &quot;If you see an iNES ROM with 3Ã—16KiB PRG banks on a mapper that doesn't support PRG banking, what does it mean?&quot;. Hence the extension to CNROM-368 and others.<br /><br />The only reason we talk about a 64KiB version of it has to do with ease of hardware implementation: a 64KiB EEPROM and a 74hc85 digital comparator is all that's needed. The different version of it using a 16KiB and 32KiB EEPROM involves more complicated hardware.<br /><br />IMO, the UNIF format should have an PRG0 field of precisely 47104 bytes. There's no reason to include the 2KiB padding that iNES requires, let alone the 18KiB that the hardware does. Regarding UNIF MAPR fields, calling it &quot;NROM-368&quot; and &quot;CNROM-368&quot; are fine; unfortunately, no such thing exists for the other boards for which the extension is well-defined (CPROM, SUNSOFT-K, CHR-less mapper 218 homebrew).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
